[[JA:己爾乃神社]]

{{wikidata link|Q11479874|ja|己爾乃神社}}

== Japanese content ==
'''Kojino Shrine''' (こじのじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Sumoto-cho, {{ill|lt=Moriyama|Q857225|qid=Q857225|1=Moriyama, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|qid=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. In the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'', under {{ill|lt=Yasu District|Q8049933|qid=Q8049933|lt=Yasu District of Ōmi Province|1=Yasu District, Shiga}}, it is listed as "Kojino Shrine, two seats," and is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}<ref>In the ''Jinmyocho'', the character for "ko" is written with a graph formed by "small" under "person." The Kujo-family annotated text reads "Kojino" as "Konino."</ref>.

Two shrines with the same name exist about 500 {{ill|lt=meters|Q11573|qid=Q11573|1=Metre}} apart. Before land reclamation, the south branch of the {{ill|lt=Yasu River|Q8049935|qid=Q8049935|1=Yasu River}} flowing from the Yasu River to {{ill|lt=Lake Biwa|Q200239|qid=Q200239|1=Lake Biwa}} ran between them, and both stood on the left-bank levee, so they are thought to originate in river-related worship<ref name="調査報告">''Shikinaisha Chosa Hokoku''.</ref>. Both preserve traditions of being the Shikinaisha, but it is geographically and historically impossible to determine one as the sole original shrine; rather, it has been pointed out that the Engishiki "Kojino Shrine" may have consisted of both shrines, which may once have had close ritual ties<ref name="調査報告"/>.

=== Kojino Shrine (Kaihatsu) ===
{{神社
|名称   = Kojino Shrine
|画像   = [[File:己爾乃神社 - panoramio.jpg|270px]]<br />Torii
|所在地 = {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|qid=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Moriyama|Q857225|qid=Q857225|1=Moriyama, Shiga}} Sumoto-cho, Kaihatsu 1607
|位置   = {{ウィキ座標2段度分秒|35|05|37.4|N|135|58|12.7|E|scale:25000}}
|祭神   = {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto|1=Izanagi|qid=Q813858}}<br/>{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Izanami-no-Mikoto|1=Izanami|qid=Q682306}}
|社格   = {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} candidate shrine / former {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}
|創建   = tradition: {{ill|lt=Tencho|Q1373138|qid=Q1373138|1=Tenchō}} 6 (829)
|本殿   = {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|qid=Q210684|lt=one-bay nagare-zukuri|1=Nagare-zukuri}}
|別名   = Kaihatsu no Kojino Shrine
|札所等 = 
|例祭   = {{ill|lt=May 5|Q2550|qid=Q2550|1=May 5}}
|神事   =
|地図   = {{Location map|Japan Shiga|label=Kojino Shrine|coordinates=
{{coord2|35|05|37.4|N|135|58|12.7|E|}}|position=bottom|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}}
{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=11|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|coord={{coord|35|05|37.4|N|135|58|12.7|E}}}}
}}
It is located in Kaihatsu, Sumoto-cho. From its location it is called "Kaihatsu no Kojino Shrine," but because a bridge called "Retsukeizu-bashi" once crossed the former south branch of the Yasu River nearby before reclamation, it was also called "Retsukeizu no Kojino Shrine"<ref name="調査報告"/>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
It enshrines {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|qid=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto|1=Izanagi}} and {{ill|lt=Izanami|Q682306|qid=Q682306|lt=Izanami-no-Mikoto|1=Izanami}} as principal deities, with {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane|Q2564508|qid=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ikatsuchi no Omi no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}} as associated deities.

Formerly the two associated deities were the principal deities under the names '''{{ill|lt=Wakaichioji|Q11616186|qid=Q11616186|1=Nyakuichi Ōji}}''' (for Ame-no-Koyane) and '''{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Wakaichi Gongen|1=UNKNOWN}}''' (for Ikatsuchi-no-Omi), but on September 22, {{ill|lt=1881|Q7808|qid=Q7808|1=1881}} (Meiji 14), they were changed to the current arrangement<ref name="調査報告"/>.

=== Origin ===
Shrine tradition says it was founded in {{ill|lt=829|Q30357|qid=Q30357|1=829}} ({{ill|lt=Tencho|Q1373138|qid=Q1373138|1=Tenchō}} 6) by Iga Atsumu. Atsumu, also called "Taifu Atsumu," is said to be a descendant of the Iga clan, whose ancestor was Iga no Suketoyo. Since the Iga clan was related to the {{ill|lt=Nakatomi clan|Q1198447|qid=Q1198447|1=Nakatomi clan}}<ref>''{{ill|lt=Shinsen Shojiroku|Q1045362|qid=Q1045362|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}}'', Sakyo Shinbetsu-jō.</ref>, it is said they enshrined Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto and Ikatsuchi-no-Omi-no-Mikoto, ancestral deities of the Nakatomi clan<ref name="神社庁開発">Shiga Prefecture Shrine Office, "[http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=463 Kojino Shrine]" (accessed Feb. 28, 2010).</ref>. Because it was often damaged by flooding of the Yasu River, only one volume titled ''Kojino Jinja no Engi-gaki'' remains, while treasures and old records were lost<ref name="調査報告"/>. There was also a shrine temple called {{ill|lt=Wakaichioji Temple (Moriyama)|UNKNOWN|lt=Wakaichioji Temple}}, and present-day {{ill|lt=Renko-ji (Moriyama)|UNKNOWN|lt=Renko-ji}} is said to continue its line. ''{{ill|lt=Omi Yochi Shiryaku|Q85883966|qid=Q85883966|1=Omi Yochi Shiryaku}}'' records a {{ill|lt=Yakushi Hall|Q11622438|qid=Q11622438|1=Bhaiṣajyaguru Hall}} near the shrine with a Buddhist image said to be made by Dengyo Daishi ({{ill|lt=Saicho|Q449943|qid=Q449943|1=Saichō}}), and this is inferred to have housed the shrine's {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=honji-butsu|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref name="調査報告"/>. Later it received a Senior First Rank {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sogen Senji|1=UNKNOWN}} from the {{ill|lt=Yoshida family|Q11413722|qid=Q11413722|1=Yoshida family}} of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Jingi Kanryo|1=UNKNOWN}}, and still preserves a sacred mirror inscribed "Senior First Rank Wakaichi Daigongen"<ref name="神社庁開発"/>. Its former rank was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

