Located in Nakanomae, Sumoto-cho. From its location it is called "Nakanomae no Kojino Shrine" and "Ōmagari no Kojino Shrine" (Ōmagari was the old local area name adjacent to Nakanomae)<ref name="調査報告"/>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
It enshrines {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōanamuji-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}, {{ill|lt=Amatsuhikone|Q10940228|qid=Q10940228|lt=Amatsuhikone-no-Mikoto|1=Amatsuhikone}}, and {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}.

=== Origin ===
Tradition says it was founded by {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Nakatomi Tamee|1=UNKNOWN}} in {{ill|lt=703|Q23500|qid=Q23500|1=703}} ({{ill|lt=Taiho (Japan)|Q1346269|qid=Q1346269|lt=Taiho|1=Taihō (era)}} 3). Though shrine buildings were lost in warfare during the {{ill|lt=Eiroku|Q1143341|qid=Q1143341|1=Eiroku}} era (1558-1570), they were restored by {{ill|lt=1791|Q7784|qid=Q7784|1=1791}} ({{ill|lt=Kansei|Q1195131|qid=Q1195131|1=Kansei}} 3). Nearby {{ill|lt=Gyokurin-ji (Moriyama)|UNKNOWN|lt=Gyokurin-ji}} was formerly its shrine temple<ref name="調査報告"/>. Its former rank was village shrine.

